        "timestamp": 1734464289
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see, I was thinking aesop would be able to find this proof since it only uses rules that it knows about</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">test</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">w</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h3</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">w</span><span class=\"o\">):</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">w</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">trans</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">trans</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h2</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h3</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Could there still be a way to make it find this proof instead or any proof using Order.trans only?</p>",
        "id": 489560825,
        "sender_full_name": "john johnson",
        "timestamp": 1734464952
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Your proof is abusing definitional equality, so is not good style. I'm not an expert in this sort of thing, but my instinct is that if Lean sees a hypothesis <code>x &lt; y</code> and it has a lemma which has hypothesis <code>Order.S x y</code> then no way will you get it to apply that lemma, because any system which allows the unfolding of <code>x &lt; y</code> is a system which will immediately grind to a halt the moment it sees the kind of monstrosities which we've constructed in <code>mathlib</code>. </p>\n<p>One approach if you're desperate to make this sort of thing work is to use <em>notation</em> <code>x &lt; y</code> to mean <code>Order.S x y</code>, instead of a typeclass, because Lean will happily look through the definition of notation. It will also look through reducible definitions, but <code>LT</code> is not your definition so you don't get to set its reducibility level.</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">notation</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"s2\">\"&lt;\"</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">-- this might have unfortunate consequences elsewhere</span>\n\n<span class=\"n\">add_aesop_rules</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">50</span><span class=\"bp\">%</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">trans</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">test</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">w</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h3</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">w</span><span class=\"o\">):</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">w</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">aesop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">-- works, because x &lt; y is now *syntactically* Order.S x y</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 489562249,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1734465478
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Another approach is to teach the system that <code>x &lt; y &lt;-&gt; S x y</code>, like this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">instance</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">LT</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">where</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">lt</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">@[</span><span class=\"n\">simp</span><span class=\"kd\">]</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">lemma</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lt_def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↔</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">S</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">rfl</span>\n\n<span class=\"n\">add_aesop_rules</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">safe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">forward</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">trans</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">test</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Order</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">w</span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h3</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">z</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">w</span><span class=\"o\">):</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">w</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">aesop</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 489563875,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1734466065
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Be warned now though that the simplifier will constantly replace <code>x &lt; y</code> with <code>S x y</code>, which may or may not be what you want.</p>",
        "id": 489563988,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1734466095
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like this second approach, my only problem is that so far it seemed harder to figure out what aesop wants to complete a proof than to just do the proof manually, and I was hoping I could use to spend less time proving \"obvious\" things. Or maybe I just don't know how to use it properly</p>",
        "id": 489565740,
        "sender_full_name": "john johnson",
        "timestamp": 1734466857
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My initial mental model of <code>aesop</code> was that it would just do everything automatically, but more recently I've come to understand that it needs training. Understanding that <code>x &lt; y</code> is syntactically (i.e. notation for) <code>LT.lt x y</code> but only definitionally <code>Order.S x y</code> is I guess important for your situation here, and I guess tagging <code>lt_def</code> <code>@[simp]</code> is solving that problem. <code>aesop</code> is not going to use lemmas it's not been told about though. One approach used in mathlib is the <code>aesop_cat</code> approach, where a bespoke trained version of <code>aesop</code> is used to prove results in category theory.</p>",
        "id": 489566223,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1734467089
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe one last thing, is there a way to make aesop use lemmas without having to mention them explicitly? For example passing an entire file and having it look for things that could be useful?</p>",
        "id": 489567222,
        "sender_full_name": "john johnson",
        "timestamp": 1734467543
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm afraid that's beyond my pay grade, I'm but a lowly mathematician. Hopefully someone else will chime in.</p>",
        "id": 489567929,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1734467868
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No problem, thanks for the help <span aria-label=\"smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f642\" role=\"img\" title=\"smile\">:smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 489568367,
        "sender_full_name": "john johnson",
        "timestamp": 1734468022
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It depends on what you mean by \"mentioning them explicitly\". The proof above is a plain call to <code>aesop</code> that does not mention any lemmas, but you have to tag lemmas first before that will work</p>",
        "id": 489568525,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1734468119
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it's similar to simp in that regard</p>",
        "id": 489568618,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1734468143
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>it does not crawl the library looking for lemmas</p>",
        "id": 489568637,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1734468153
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the only tactics I'm aware of that do that are <code>exact?</code> and <code>apply?</code></p>",
        "id": 489568669,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1734468173
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I understand, I was wondering if there is a way to make it behave like exact? in that sense or maybe an alternative with that behaviour</p>",
        "id": 489570097,
        "sender_full_name": "john johnson",
        "timestamp": 1734468759
    }
]